  "prompt": "Should I switch from Computer Engineering to Computer Science?",
  "response": "That depends on several factors:\n\nComputer Engineering pros:\n- More hardware-focused\n- Often includes electrical engineering components\n- Can lead to roles designing computer systems\n- Typically involves more low-level programming\n- May have better job opportunities in embedded systems\n\nComputer Science pros:\n- More software-focused\n- Broader programming skills\n- More emphasis on algorithms and theoretical computing\n- More flexibility in career paths\n- Often easier to transition between different software domains\n\nConsider switching if:\n1. You prefer software development over hardware design\n2. You enjoy high-level programming languages\n3. You want more flexibility in career choices\n4. You're more interested in software architecture and design\n\nStay in Computer Engineering if:\n1. You enjoy working with hardware\n2. You're interested in embedded systems\n3. You like low-level programming\n4. You want to understand computer architecture deeply\n\nRecommendations:\n- Talk to professors/advisors\n- Speak with professionals in both fields\n- Consider your personal interests and career goals\n- Compare course requirements\n- Potentially take some classes in both domains before deciding\n\nUltimately, the best choice depends on your individual interests and career aspirations.",
